message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient’s symptoms and examination findings suggest a missed miscarriage. The elevated β-HCG level and ultrasonography findings suggest trophoblastic proliferation with chorionic villi distention, which is consistent with a missed miscarriage. Placenta implantation into myometrium (placenta accreta) and malpositioned placenta overlying the cervix (placenta previa) are complications of pregnancy but are not likely in this case. Malignant transformation of trophoblastic tissue (choriocarcinoma) is a rare complication of a complete or partial molar pregnancy but this patient's presentation is not consistent with that diagnosis.

This is consistent with trophoblastic proliferation with chorionic villi distention, which is the most likely cause of her condition. Placenta implantation into the myometrium and malpositioned placenta overlying the cervix are complications of a traditional pregnancy, while malignant transformation of trophoblastic tissue is a complication of a molar pregnancy that has become invasive.
